---
description: MoonDB schema and API conventions for building backends
alwaysApply: true
---

moondb-conventions:

- MoonDB uses declarative JSON schemas. Describe WHAT you want, not HOW — never write SQL.
- Always send the full schema on updates. MoonDB auto-diffs and migrates.
- Column types: string, text, int, float, bool, date, datetime, timestamp, json, enum, ref, uuid, file.
- Short-form syntax: "string required unique", "int default 0", "ref users required", "bool default true".
- IDs are UUID v4, auto-generated. Never define `id`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `email` (on auth tables), or `password_hash` columns.
- For auth tables set `auth_table: true` — this auto-creates `email` (string, required, unique) and `password_hash`, and enables /auth/* endpoints.
- Access levels: "public", "authenticated", "owner", "admin". Default is "authenticated" for all operations.
- When any access rule is "owner", set `owner_field` to a ref column pointing to the auth table (e.g. "user_id"). MoonDB compares it with the user id from the JWT — users only see/edit their own rows. Auto-filled on INSERT from Bearer token. For auth_table itself use `"owner_field": "id"`.
- Refs are always to the `id` column. on_delete options: cascade, restrict (default), set_null.
- Enum values must match [a-zA-Z0-9_-] only.
- Destructive schema changes (drop column, narrow enum) require `confirm_destructive: true`.
- Auth keys: X-Admin-Key (sk_...) for management, Authorization: Bearer for user auth, X-Public-Key (pk_...) for public reads.
- Every error response includes a `suggestion` field — always read it to self-correct.
